Picquigny, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":62,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":71,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas FitzBernard was born about 1153, in Badlesmere, Kent, England, his father, Sir Thomas FitzBarnard, was 29 and his mother, Agnes de Picquigny, was 25. He married Eugenia Picot in 1173, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1225, in Kingsdown, Kent, England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"about 1153–about 1225":"umbes 1153–umbes 1225","1153–1225":"1153–1225","1154–1184":"1154–1184","1175–1214":"1175–1214","1175–1254":"1175–1254","1125–1184":"1125–1184","1130–1165":"1130–1165","about 1184":"umbes 1184"